title: Implement Runtime Permission Library
message:
Implement Runtime Permission Library

Well the temporary solution of compiling to API 22 failed. Turns out you're not allowed to downgrade
from API 23 due to the fact that the permission logic was already enforced for Marshmallow users.
The Runtime Permissions really irked me and I despised the fact that it bloats the codebase. So I
used a library that autogenerates classes for me to handle all that crap. I hope Google considers
the developers point of views in future updates.

title: Fixes #34
message:
Fixes #34

Having a scrollview as the absolute parent to all fragments was pretty stupid.
It makes much more sense to add a scrollview when it's necessary.
Also having a listview inside a scrollview is widely discouraged among the android community, and
for good reason too. They both have their own scrolling events to take care of, and it'd be weird to
have them both react to the same scroll event.

title: Redesign model storage architecture.
message:
Redesign model storage architecture.

I just realized that in order to submit the order on shapeways, I would need both the g3db file for
viewing, in addition to the stl file for uploading.

Now every model will have it's own folder with a unique name, typically the name of the image.
The folder will now contain both the g3db file as well as the stl file.

title: Integrate code into a LibGDX project.
message:
Integrate code into a LibGDX project.

I'm going to have to apologize for this massive disruption in project history. When I began this project, I thought it would be easier to simply program all the android specific code first, and then transitionit into a LibGDX project. I did not have clean project history in mind when I made this decision. This is still essentially the same application as the previous commit.

Fixes #25

title: Change logic for obtaining 3d files.
message:
Change logic for obtaining 3d files.

Rather than attempting to obtain an stl file from the shapeJS server and convert it to a g3db on the phone (which is taxing and a bad idea in the first place, not to mention extremely difficult), the application will communicate with a custom server. That custom server will retrieve an image file, communicate with shapeJS, convert the received 3d file (twice), and return it to the application. A link to the server code will be provided within the Readme, along with the utilized conversion libraries.
